An Introduction to Aviation Debt:
Enhanced Equipment Trust Certificates (EETCs),
Aircraft Asset-Backed Securities (ABS), SGR Financings,
and other types of Aviation Secured Debt

- Growth and fleet replacement drive new deliveries.- Commercial aircraft fleet size is expected to double over next two decades.- Fleet will likely reach \(\sim 50,000\) aircraft by 2044.- Worldwide requirement of new passenger aircraft in next 20 years is valued at more than \$4 trillion.- Most new deliveries require financing and some of existing fleet require refinancing.
Fleet growth and replacement estimates
New aircraft delivery financing sources (2009 to 2016 & 2017 to current)

After Covid, capital markets likely will provide an increasing percentage of the financing for the growing value of new aircraft deliveries, as well as refinancing used aircraft.- Issuance of EETCs has been limited in the last two years as a result of widening interest rates and spreads and the availability of attractive financing in the sale- leaseback market for new aircraft deliveries. Aircraft ABS market, in contrast, is very active in refinancing existing aircraft.
Global Air Traffic vs. External Shocks

- Pandemic-induced decline in traffic was unprecedented in the history of modern commercial aviation.- Air traffic has historically rebounded from previous disruptions, including 9/11, SARS and the Global Finance Crisis. It has rebounded this time as well, with full recovery from Covid achieved in 2023-2024 and good growth in 2025.
Global Air Traffic – Good growth in most regions year-to-date

- Global traffic saw a modest increase in June 2025, with traffic up 2.6% year-over-year, up 5.1% year-to-date.

- Asia Pacific, the region that was slowest to recover from the pandemic, saw a large improvement in June 2025, with traffic up 5.0% year-over-year and 8.6% year-to-date. Latin America had good growth, with traffic up 7.9% year-over-year and 7.6% year-to-date.
- North America is soft, with low-cost carriers making significant reductions in capacity and majors moderating capacity expansion plans.
Global Capacity – Robust recovery across regions since Covid
Global Airlines Capacity (% change vs. same period 2019)
- Virtually all major air travel regions have capacity levels above 2019 levels, with load factors often running at record levels.
- Growth in Central America, Latin America and India has been especially strong.
- China domestic capacity is at high levels, but some long-haul international travel lags.
Global Capacity – Solid growth in capacity in 4Q2025
Global Airlines Capacity (% Y-o-Y change)
- Most regions of the world have solid increases in capacity scheduled for the remainder of 2025, with Singapore showing some downward adjustment.

- August 2025 month-to-date: 102% versus August 2024 month-to-date
Airline industry net post-tax profits, USD bn

- International Air Transport Association (IATA) figures show significant improvement in reported results in 2023, modest reductions in profitability in 2024 and some improvement in 2025, aided by low oil prices.
- Profitability is concentrated – average rating of global airlines is single-B category.
Airline outlook – Improved profitability expected in 2025
Global Airline Industry Financial Results: Yearly Results and Forecast

- Global airline financial results, after falling to horrific levels during the depths of Covid-induced travel restrictions and demand destruction in 2020, returned to profitability in 2023. Profitability slipped slightly in 2024, with some improvement expected in 2025, according to IATA forecasts.
- Aggregate profitability and margins are highest in North America, as they were prior to the start of the pandemic.
Note: Break-up of heat map: Green: EBIT margins, Net profits > 0%; Yellow: 0% < Profitability > -5%; Red: Profitability < -5%. Source: IATA, Deutsche Bank
Parked Passenger Jets – Jul 2025 vs. Jun 2025, Jul 2024 & Jul 2019
- Every age cohort of both narrowbody and widebody passenger aircraft saw sequential improvement in storage from June 2025 to July 2025, with most also showing significant improvement year-over-year.

- The improvement in storage rate was due almost wholly to aircraft returning to service (shrinking the numerator of the calculation) as well as a new aircraft deliveries increasing the size of the total fleet (the denominator in the calculation), rather than aircraft being scrapped
- Storage rate is broadly and inversely, if imperfectly, correlated with aircraft lease rates and values.
Age Distribution of Parked Passenger Aircraft (p.p. change sequentially) - July 2025

- Excluding forced storage of GTF-powered aircraft, storage of narrowbody aircraft improved sequentially from 7.5% in June 2025 to 6.9% in July 2025, moving closer to the pre-pandemic storage rate of 4.8% in July 2019.

- Storage of middle-aged narrowbody aircraft improved materially, as airlines return older aircraft to service in the absence of new deliveries and continues the grounding of over 600 GTF-powered narrowbody aircraft.

- Storage of new 737 MAX family aircraft, which are powered solely by CFM LEAP engines, had a storage rate of 1.6% for the 737 MAX 8 and 0.7% for the 737 MAX 9, as close to "full employment" as you will see given need for periodic maintenance.
Narrowbody (Excl. RJs) Western Passenger Aircraft - Operating Status (LTM)
Storage rates for western- built narrowbody passenger aircraft types improved year- over- year and sequentially in July 2025.
Year- over- year: Improved from 10.0% in Jul 2024 to 9.8% in Jul 2025.
Sequentially: Improved from 10.5% in Jun 2025 to 9.8% in Jul 2025.
Narrowbody storage inflated by forced grounding of GTF- powered aircraft.
Aircraft Stored: A220/A320neo family operating GTF & LEAP Engines
- The travails of Pratt & Whitney's GTF-engine, which powers roughly half of the Airbus A320neo family and all of the Airbus A220 family of aircraft, continues.

- Storage of GTF-powered A320neo family aircraft fell in July and August, falling to 34% in August 2025. On an absolute basis, storage of GTF-powered A320neo family aircraft remains exceptionally high, with approximately 600 nearly new aircraft stored at the end of August 2024.
- For operators of GTF-powered A320neo family aircraft and, to a lesser extent, GTF-powered A220 family aircraft, engine availability remains an issue.
Widebodies: Newer planes in demand, older a bit less so
Widebody Western Passenger Aircraft - Operating Status (LTM)
- Storage for western-built widebody passenger aircraft types improved year over year and sequentially in July 2025.
- Year over year: Improved from 12.2% in Jul 2024 to 10.0% in Jul 2025.
- Sequentially: Improved from 10.6% in Jun 2025 to 10.0% in Jul 2025.
- Widebody market was soft prior to the onset of Covid in early 2020, with the pandemic widening the gap between narrowbody and widebody storage rates.
- Widebody storage rates have come down significantly and are moving much closer to narrowbody storage rates.
- Widebody storage rates remain higher than narrowbody storage rates for older age cohorts.

- Market is particularly challenging for "teenage" widebody aircraft, where reconfiguration and overhaul costs along with MRO capacity can represent a significant obstacle to transitioning the aircraft to a new operator.
Mainline Passenger Fleet Composition - by Aircraft Class
- The split between narrowbody and widebody mainline passenger aircraft has made a slow, but inexorable move in favor of narrowbodies over the last 25 years.
- The current backlog of undelivered mainline passenger aircraft indicates this trend is likely to continue at an accelerating pace over the next five to seven years, we believe.
Narrowbody Passenger Aircraft Backlog by Manufacturer

- Airbus increasingly dominates the backlog for narrowbody passenger aircraft. The Airbus market share benefits both from the earlier entry into service of the A320neo family (2016) versus the 737 MAX family (2017), the production halt of the 737 MAX beginning in 2019, as well as the better operational capabilities and availability of the A321neo versus its Boeing competitors, the 737 MAX 9 and 737 MAX 10.
Widebody Passenger Aircraft Backlog - by Manufacturer
- Boeing dominates the backlog of widebody passenger aircraft, with an approximately 60% share.
- Lessons and airlines (who make up the bulk of widebody orders and backlog versus the lessors) are, in our opinion, very under-ordered on widebody passenger aircraft.
Western Mainline Passenger Total Fleet vs. Storage

- We expect the market for narrowbody passenger aircraft to improve significantly over the next several years, for both new technology narrowbodies (e.g., 737 MAX and A320neo) as well as current technology narrowbodies (e.g., 737 NG and A320ceo). We believe that the storage rate for narrowbody passenger aircraft will move well below that which existed in 2019 prior to the start of Covid.

Previous generation narrowbody aircraft should represent a majority of the market for narrowbody aircraft for at least the next three to four years, we believe. This should create continued demand for previous generation narrowbody aircraft over the next several years, we believe.
We believe that middle- aged previous generation narrowbody aircraft should benefit from growing demand for narrowbody aircraft until eventual retirement.
Mainline Aircraft Deliveries by Aircraft Class - Airbus & Boeing

- The halt in delivery of Boeing's 737 MAX beginning in 2019 and Boeing's 787 in 2021, reduced airline demand for aircraft during Covid, and struggles to increase production as Covid faded and traffic returned have created a "lost generation" of passenger aircraft that otherwise would have been built between 2019 and 2022.  
- More than 2,000 fewer narrowbody aircraft and 750 fewer widebody aircraft were delivered between 2019 and 2024 than would have been the case if 2018 delivery rates had been maintained through the period.
Recovery of aircraft value: Constant age Airbus & Boeing aircraft

- New narrowbody (i.e., single-aisle) and widebody (i.e., twin-aisle) passenger aircraft have shown market values that are far more resilient than their older, previous generation siblings such as the 737-800 (narrowbody) and A330-300 (widebody) through the depths of Covid. The more volatile performance of older aircraft during downturns is a common phenomenon that we have seen through many downcycles, as airlines shed older, less-fuel efficient aircraft.
Introduction to Secured Aviation Debt Products
- Enhanced Equipment Trust Certificates (EETCs) are a form of secured, recourse airline corporate debt with a security interest in a pool of commercial aircraft.
- \(\) 90+\(billion of EETCs issued from 20+ airlines across 120+ transactions.

- Since 2009, secured aircraft issuance from airlines and lessors exceeded \(\) 100\(billion, of which\) \ \(42+\) billion was sold in EETC format. 
- EETC issuance volume correlated with volume of new aircraft deliveries.
- EETCs are used both to finance new deliveries and refinance older aircraft.
- Approximately \(\) 20\(billion of EETCs currently outstanding.
- Only one EETC issue in 2025 as US airlines focus on deleveraging and new aircraft deliveries lag.

- EETCs are a form of secured airline corporate debt with significantly higher credit ratings/credit quality than unsecured airline corporate debt.

- Under Section 1110 of the US Bankruptcy Code, bondholders can seize aircraft collateral in 60 days if the airline defaults.- 7th Circuit Decision allows co-operation among creditors and enhances negotiating leverage with an airline in a default.- Non-US jurisdictions may be subject to provisions of Cape Town Treaty and/or local law that provides for similarly rapid remedies to certificate holders.
- Aviation Working Group (AWG) provides rating of Cape Town compliance publicly (www.awg.aero)
- Cape Town may not always work perfectly, but can help even in difficult jurisdictions that have less-than-predictable local law environments, we believe.
Standard EETC Structural Elements

- Liquidity support: 18 months of liquidity (typically more for non-US EETCs) covering three interest payments to provide sufficient time to repossess and remarket any aircraft repossessed in a default without a payment default on interest for all tranches of virtually all issues.
- Liquidity facility is only available to pay interest.
- There is no liquidity facility or other dedicated source of funds at inception for any repossession/remarketing and other expenses if needed after an airline bankruptcy.

- Tranching and Cross-subordination: Redirection of cash from junior notes to senior notes in default to provide protection to senior tranches. Senior tranche generally is the controlling party in the event of a default and directs rights and remedies (eg, aircraft repossession).
- Higher Ratings: As a result of these security provisions, EETCs generally have ratings between one and nine "notches" above the airline's unsecured rating.
Multiple classes of debt tranched by seniority: AA, A, B and C

- Prior to 2016, A-tranche was the senior-most tranche.- Beginning in 2016, AA-tranche is the senior-most tranche.- A-tranche, given rating downgrades, is the senior-most tranche again.- D-tranche issued, but very rarely and not in recent history.- "Super" tranches can be issued, combining a tranche class from multiple EETC issues into a single tranche (e.g., Spirit Airlines).- Airline may retain the right to later issue additional sub tranches.- Higher tranches have lower (ie, better) loan-to-values (LTVs) and ratings.- Lower tranches have higher (ie, worse) loan-to-values (LTVs) and ratings.- Senior tranches tend to have longer maturities than subordinate tranches.- LTVs protected by matching amortization of debt to expected depreciation of planes.
Senior classes have controlling position and higher priority claim on collateral in event of default.
When senior tranche wrapped, the policy provider is the controlling party. Liquidity facility provider can become controlling party if not repaid in a certain period.
Junior classes can buy out senior classes at par in a bankruptcy (triggering event varies).

Creates negative convexity for senior tranches (not as relevant for issues trading below par). Buy- out right used aggressively in pre- 2007 bankruptcies due to above market coupons rather than to protect position of subordinate tranches. Post- 2007 changes to structure make "interest arbitrage" buy- outs more difficult.
US airlines almost certainly have right to repay debt in bankruptcy at par plus accrued interest if it is economically advantageous.
When the airline is not in bankruptcy, cash flow from airline on equipment notes matches EETC P&l exactly.
Payments may not be modified by airline outside of bankruptcy.

If aircraft are parked, payments must be made in full (or in certain cases, certificates called). If aircraft have declined in value, payments must be made in full. If an aircraft is lost, there is a pro rata par call (aircraft is required to be insured) or substitution.

If an airline enters bankruptcy, it has the option in the first 60 days under Section 1110(a) of the bankruptcy code, to retain control of the aircraft by agreeing to make payments in full. If an airline exercises Section 1110(a), you cannot repossess aircraft unless there is a later default.
- 1110(a) is an affirmation, not an assumption or reinstatement.
- Occurs rarely and is not costless, but airline can renege on an 1110(a) election in bankruptcy.
- Aircraft financed with EETCs are usually important/essential to an airline's operation, improving bondholders' likelihood of a full recovery, even in the event of an airline bankruptcy.
- Post-9/11 structure with cross-collateralization and, especially, cross-default, improves security for bondholders and protects less-desirable aircraft collateral within EETC transactions.
- Airline can no longer "cherry pick" aircraft to affirm and reject without bondholder consent in bankruptcy.
- This change is a significant strengthening of the structure.
- In late 2019, structure was altered to allow substitution of aircraft.

- Can substitute any aircraft at any time for any reason.  
- Aircraft do not need to be same type (but sometimes same class).  
- Age must be the same or younger.  
- Value must be same or higher (but "value" not well defined).  
- Ratings must not be negatively affected.
- This change is a material weakening of the structure, we believe. But market doesn't seem to care.
- Most EETC aircraft are a desirable and core part of an airline's fleet.
- Common aircraft include the Airbus A320 family and Boeing 737 family, along with Airbus A320neo and Boeing 737 MAX.
- Some less attractive aircraft (eg, CRJs, RJ85s, MD80s) have also been financed in distant past.
- Use of EETC for refinancing aircraft means EETC aircraft are not necessarily the youngest in an airline's fleet, as was the case with earlier EETCs.

- Average DB Marketability Grade of aircraft in EETCs.  
- Average Post-9/11 EETC Deal aircraft Rating: 3.4/4.0
- What has to go wrong for EETC tranches to be impaired -- a lot!
- "Stalking Horse" bid for aircraft- Restrictive auction procedures- Sale of aircraft- Investor lawsuit- Litigation settled privately
Historic Recovery to date
EETCs have proven to be remarkably resilient, with EETC senior holders unimpaired even after an airline bankruptcy in virtually all cases.

- Airlines entered into an unprecedented level of borrowing, often secured by unencumbered assets, in 2020 and 2021 to survive revenue destruction.

- Issuance of public debt in 2022, 2023 and 2024 is modest, as airlines rebuild balance sheets and use cash to pay for aircraft to rebuild unencumbered assets. Improved airline profitability in 2023-2025 further reduces need for airline debt issuance in the near term.

Note: Market Data as of August 26, 2025
Source: Bloomberg Finance LP, Finsight, Deutsche Bank
- AerCap acquisition of GECAS and subsequent long-term financing boosted issuance in 2021.
- Issuance in 2023-254 returning towards a normalized level, but somewhat limited by delayed delivery of new aircraft.
Aircraft ABS New Issue: 2001 – 2019 (i.e., pre-pandemic)
- After a drought of several years, aircraft ABS issuance grew significantly from 2013 to 2019.
- The aircraft ABS market set a record for issuance in 2019, before issuance plunged with the onset of the pandemic in 2020.

- 13 aviation ABS transactions priced in 2021, with total issuance of approximately $8.4bn. The invasion of Ukraine by Russia and widening spreads slowed issuance in 2022. The slowdown in aircraft ABS issuance continued into 2023, but aircraft ABS market reopened in 2024 with accelerating issuance in 2025.
- Aircraft ABS average lease revenue plunged in 2020 as airlines defaulted and others sought rent deferrals and rent reductions.
- Aircraft ABS average lease revenue climbed in 2023, 2024 and 2025, driven in large part by strong increases in aircraft sales. Debt Service Coverage Ratio (DSCR) has climbed as well.
Avg. Revenue (\$,000s)

- Aircraft sales from outstanding aircraft ABS transactions have accelerated over the last two years as servicers take advantage of a strong market for secondary aircraft sales.- Aircraft sales are frequently at levels at or above Adjusted Base Value of the aircraft, with proceeds used to reduce outstanding debt balances.

- Aircraft sales from aircraft ABS transactions have been accelerating in 2025, with most aircraft sales made at a premium to Adjusted Base Value.- Aircraft sales are benefitting from a strong market for secondary market aircraft, particularly previous generation narrowbody aircraft (e.g., A320ceo, 737 NG) that are prevalent in aircraft ABS transactions.
Average Rent Payments and Utilization Rent per Aircraft

Average rent per aircraft troughed in July 2020 at just over \(\) 100,000\(and has since nearly doubled. Initial recovery was driven largely by repaying rent deferred during the pandemic, but more recently by a strengthening aircraft market.
The increase in average rent per aircraft is particularly impressive as it has occurred against the headwind of the average age of aircraft in benchmark transactions increasing.

Aircraft ABS Secondary Trading Price Analysis

- Aircraft ABS trading prices fell sharply with the onset of Covid in 1H2020, before recovering in 2H2020 and into 2021.- The Russian invasion of Ukraine along with steadily higher Treasury rates and wider spreads resulted in softening prices in 2022 for most senior and junior tranches.- Improving fundamentals have driven higher prices in 2024
Other collateral can include hard and soft (i.e., intangible) collateral

- Engines and aircraft spare parts- Ground equipment- Simulators- Maintenance facilities and other real estate- Accounts receivable and cash- Loyalty programs- Slots, gates and routes- While often pledged together, these three are each a distinct type of asset

- Spares, if in a sufficiently large pool and cross-defaulted, are usually very important if not essential to original airline obligor's operations and ability to restructure successfully in bankruptcy.- Spares often new and virtually certain to be subject to Section 1110.- Spares generally have more transparent pricing than aircraft.- Aircraft parts are a worldwide commodity and are mobile assets.- Demand for spares is not normally fully correlated geographically.- Spares can be transported around the world to where need is greatest.
- Collateral can consist of thousands of parts among numerous different locations.
- Where are "my" parts?- May be physically challenging to repossess, particularly in liquidation.

- Spares have little value without a chain of control and records.- Where are "my" records and where have "my" spares been since birth?- May be challenging to obtain and verify, particularly in liquidation.
Ground equipment, simulators, real estate, maintenance facilities

- Real estate (like a headquarters) may be worth something to someone other than an airline, improving marketability.- Ground equipment (tugs, carts, belt loaders, etc.) can literally be driven away and easily moved to another carrier if repossessed.- Sims are in demand for popular aircraft types and are mobile (to some degree).

- Ground equipment depreciates rapidly, can be "lost" and is easily replaced.- Maintenance facilities are usually tailored to a specific airline and are of little use to other potential airline users; maintenance facilities often have little value for non-airline uses.- Simulators depreciate more rapidly than aircraft.- Simulators are specific to a particular aircraft type.- Simulators may not be of significant value to many other airlines.- Real estate may or may not be attractive given location and design features.
Slots, Gates, Routes (these are not synonyms)
The right to take off and land at a particular airport with physical capacity limitations (generally runways and related air- traffic control constraints) at a particular hour.

A leasehold on a lease or other airport agreement that generally provides the right to use a particular jetway and associated holdroom (ie, waiting area) for a finite period. Gates and associated airport facilities can generally not be pledged or mortgaged directly, since they are usually owned by an airport or municipality or airport corporation; instead, a leasehold is granted.

The authorization, usually under treaty or other inter- governmental agreement, for an airline to fly between one or more city pairs in different countries. Route authorities with service limitations are becoming rare and are increasingly replaced with "Open Skies" agreements, which effectively allow unlimited service (subject to other non- regulatory constraints).
Slots, Gates, Routes (these are not synonyms)

Strengths:- Routes, slots and gates can be very valuable if scarce (and they each often are).- Can often not be replicated easily or at all by the operating airline or its competitors.- Slots at physical constrained airports are extremely valuable, as it is impossible to operate at such an airport without them.- Leaseholds on gates can be similarly valuable at physically constrained airports - many airports have no room for terminal expansions, or an expansion would take many years with many obstacles and at great cost.

Weaknesses:- Transfer or sale of routes may be politically challenging, even if nominally permitted.- Route authorities can be modified / revoked / changed or competing route authorities granted by unilateral government action.- Slots can be modified / revoked / changed by unilateral government action.- Route authorities increasingly rare and even anachronistic, as they are replaced with "Open Skies" agreements.- Security interest in leaseholds on gates may not necessarily be perfected, recorded or transferable.
Long but distant history of route authorities being used as collateral and sold to others.

Pan Am's Pacific Routes to United in 1980s. TWA's London Routes to American in 1990s. Pan Am's Latin Routes to United in 1990s. Few recent transfers, as restrictive route authorities generally replaced with "Open Skies." Open Skies generally allow unlimited flying between two or more countries. Collateral often used in Exit Facilities and explicitly approved by the Court at exit. Collateral pledge of routes and related collateral not challenged in airline bankruptcies since at least 2000, that we are aware of.

Leasehold mortgage can be transferred, but rarely that we are aware of. Continental/Eastern Terminal at LaGuardia to US Airways and ultimately to Delta. Granting of leasehold is often not perfected or otherwise recorded. Transfer of leasehold may be precluded by agreements with airport or other parties. "..it is likely that most, or possibly all, gate leaseholds included in the collateral will be unavailable to satisfy obligations under the notes in the event of foreclosure on the collateral, and you should not rely on the value of any gate leaseholds...."
- Frequently used as collateral and sold to others, but may transfer may require government involvement.

- Various carriers purchasing LGA slots from Delta.- Various carriers purchasing DCA slots from US Airways.- Various carriers purchasing LHR slots from others, including recently. Sale of slots at LHR after carrier liquidation once contested, but now court approved.- Sales may be mandated or precluded by regulators in conjunction with competition concerns.- Slots are typically authorized by government decisions and can be changed (ie, EWR).- The most tangible of intangible aviation collateral, we believe.

- Typically performed by a single appraiser, generally ISTAT-certified.- Generally based on the profitability of the entire network associated with SGR, not a sum of the value of the slots, gates and routes individually.- No effort generally made to value gates or routes, although value of slots may be discussed.- Valuation is made based on detailed internal cost accounting that is not available publicly.- Use of discount rate range and terminal value assumptions determined by appraiser.- These assumptions can significantly change valuations.
Relatively new form of financing for the airline sector.

Pledges assets that are critical and likely essential for airline in bankruptcy. Affirmation factor appears very high in an operating bankruptcy. Significant rating uplift as a result of high affirmation factor.
Value of assets if extremely high to issuing airline, much less so to others. Liquidation of airline would likely cause severe impairment to security.

Cash flow generation of pledged assets dependent on contractual arrangements between parties that represents, for the airline, a form of internal transfer value (eg, price of miles sold versus miles redeemed).

Assets are intangible and not subject to Section 1110 as are aircraft and parts. Contractual features and cash flow pledge may provide significant inducement for airline to continue payments in bankruptcy even in the absence of Section 1110.
What is value of a Loyalty Program of a demised airline? Or an airline to which few customers may have any loyalty at all? Spirit bankruptcy offers lessons.
A fundamental question for “essential” secured debt with an expectation of affirmation in an operating bankruptcy:

When all or a substantial part of an airline's capital structure consists of debt secured by “essential” assets that seemingly “require” affirmation in order for the airline to successfully restructure and emerge from bankruptcy...
...is every creditor secured, or is no creditor secured?

- Type: Arrangement of seats on either side of the aisle(s) in a typical coach configuration.- Design Seats: Manufacturer's indicative seating in one, two or three-class configuration / Maximum one-class seating based on government regulations (i.e., exit limits) or technical limitations.- Actual Seats: The average and median of the estimated in-use seating capacity of each aircraft in the current fleet.- Deliveries: Years that the aircraft was delivered to customers or is expected to be delivered to commercial customers. This number may differ from the first and/or last build year.- Engines: Division of engine type by number of units for current fleet and aircraft on order.- Fuel/Thrust: Fuel capacity of aircraft (rounded to nearest hundreds) / Maximum specified thrust available on aircraft variant (rounded to nearest thousands) x number of engines.- Range: Manufacturer's specified range of most capable version of aircraft type in nautical miles and equivalents.- MTOW: Manufacturer's specified maximum takeoff weight. Length/Span: Exterior length of aircraft and its wingspan.- Fleet/In-Service/Stored: Number of aircraft that are in-service or stored / Number of aircraft in-service / Number of aircraft stored but not yet permanently retired (all numbers from Cirium).- Fleet Age/Backlog (%)/Retired (%): Average age of fleet / Aircraft on order but not delivered (backlog as a % of the total fleet) / Aircraft retired or scrapped, excluding conversions (retired/scrapped as % of all aircraft built)- Operators: In-Service/Fleet/Total: Number of operators with aircraft in-service/Number of operators with aircraft in-service or parked/Number of operators with aircraft in-service, parked or on order.- HHI: In-Service/Fleet/Total: The HHI of the aircraft type calculated for (1) all planes in-service; (2) all planes in-service and parked and (3) all planes in-service, parked and on order. HHI (Herfindahl-Hirschman Index) measures concentration - from 10,000 (one operator has 100% of fleet) to near zero (a large number of operators with a small number of aircraft each).- Grade/Outlook: The marketability of the type ranging from 0.0 ("F") to 4.0 ("A"). Evaluates the relative difficulty of placing an aircraft type as a passenger aircraft. The grade does not take into account the viability or attractiveness of the aircraft for freighter conversion. Outlook is potential direction of grade in 1-3 years.
